The login name of the user's domain account. We only allow
accounts explicitly added to log into the local machine.
The password for the user's domain account. This is used to:
a) fail early if the user's login name or password is incorrect
b) by default we try to use this to enroll the machine in the domain.
It also makes the dialog for administrative credentials (below)
clearer. If these credentials fail to enroll the machine, then we know
that the administrative credentials are needed and can explain this.
While the user fills in the rest of the dialog we can
check that it's a valid domain or realm.
In order to use enterprise logins, this computer needs to be
enrolled in the domain. Please have your network Administrator
This dialog is meant for both the user and the network administrator.
It must be clear to the network administrator what is going on, and
We can guess at what the administrator name might be and prefill.
Many small networks use the default administrator name.
